In its nicely produced publication `` <ENAMEX TYPE="WORK_OF_ART">Where Will Our Children Live ?</ENAMEX> '' the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">NAHB</ENAMEX> does acknowledge that `` of course , the full measure of housing affordability can not be provided by the federal government . ''
It points to the pernicious impact of local government regulation , particularly zoning and building fees , which pushes the price of housing out of the reach of low - and middle - income people .
But while the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">NAHB</ENAMEX> has suggested actions that states and localities should take to reduce regulatory barriers , the association has proposed no activist legislative program -- comparable to , say , its detailed request for more federal subsidies -- to eliminate counterproductive controls .
The association , a majority of whose <ENAMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">156,000</ENAMEX> members build <ENAMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">fewer than 25</ENAMEX> units a year , is like many other business lobbies .
Explains <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sheila MacDonald</ENAMEX> of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">the National Taxpayers Union</ENAMEX> : `` It treads in <ENAMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">two</ENAMEX> worlds .
The builders like the subsidies , but at the same time they tend to be fiscal conservatives in terms of major issues , such as the balanced - budget amendment . ''
Unfortunately , the organization 's desire for pork tends to override its commitment to overall fiscal responsibility .
<ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">Two years ago</ENAMEX> when the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">NAHB</ENAMEX> lobbied for the <ENAMEX TYPE="MONEY">$ 19 billion</ENAMEX> omnibus housing bill , the organization `` basically dropped out of the taxpayers ' coalition , '' says Ms. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MacDonald</ENAMEX> .
